However, it's important to remember that everyone's journey is different, and comparing yourself to others can lead to feelings of unhappiness and dissatisfaction with your own life. Additionally, it's not fair to generalize or stereotype people based on their profession or income level.

It's important to focus on your own goals and aspirations, and to work towards achieving them. Money is not the only measure of success, and there are many other ways to be happy and fulfilled. You can also try to find hobbies or activities that you enjoy and that will help you to relax and de-stress.

Keep in mind that it's also not fair to connect your income with your love life, as many factors contribute to a relationship and it's not fair to generalize that one's income level will affect the chances of having a successful relationship.

It's also important to remember that you are not alone in feeling this way, and it's okay to reach out for support if you need it.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
you've got to turn your invisible hinderances into visible nuisances and reminders

1 - absolutely go overboard with alarms, reminders, etc
2 - learn to time block almost everything and be very strict about the activity that you've allocated some time into
3 - start with a simple system and expand from there, otherwise you risk feeling good about over-tinkering with a complex system and you acquire the false sensation that you're doing something meaningful ("productive procrastination") (in the end it's too complex for you to use without some sort of deeply ingrained routine)

I have ADHDpracticeuse stims very sparingly, basically in the 10 days prior to my finals or something similar (+ concentration, + consistent attention, - time blindness during revisions and exams)

takes a lot of work but I'm top of my class in a very demanding field, good luck op

>>69635117
The point of the "do what comes naturally" advice in the OP is that too many new runners read something about how the best in the world run and deliberately try to mimic that style. They injure themselves in the process because they are in no way capable of running like that.

As you start running longer distances and more miles, your body will come to an equilibrium that allows it to run efficiently. With self-discipline, this process of discovery can be injury-free. (Trying to run 10 miles when you've only got the strength to run 2 is asking for trouble.)

With regards to the chunky shoes, the thickness of the midsole is only one part of it. The padding is very nice for comfort over long runs. The shape is important as well. The toe ramp (the way the sole curves up at the front) allows you to smoothly push off, transitioning from a nice mid-foot landing to to toe-off without having to waste energy fighting to flex a stiff sole.

>>69636348
>I wonder studies exist comparing injuries for forefooters with heelstrikers

If both groups are wearing the same shoe, run at the same pace, and have the same level of fitness and experience, injury rates are identical.
A fatso running on his toes will hurt something as easily as he would if he ran on his heels.

The interesting phenomenon is when you compare shoes to barefooters.

The shoe-wearing runners tended to hurt their knees, while the barefooters tended to hurt their ankles, but the barefooters ran about half the cumulative distance as the shoe-wearers. The rate of injury per kilometer run was basically the same. (Having broken my ankle before, I wouldn't say an ankle injury is preferable to a knee injury.)

>Who is /fat/ for?
For carbed-up chuds who are working towards a better physique through meaningful hard-work, strategy, and dedication. This is not QTDDTOT, stick to questions on fat loss. Post height and weight when asking for advice.
Join our Fatty Contest: https://www.fattycontest.com/

>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

>Now what?
Count calories, all of them.
Eat about 500-1000 less calories than your TDEE.
Buy scales, be accurate.
Learn to cook. Try to stick to lean protein and green vegetables.
Eat a lot of protein. 0.72g per lb of goal lean body mass.
Doing cardio, even just walking, will improve your health. There is no such thing as a healthy fat heart, but you can offset the risks.
Lifting weights will keep and gain muscle mass and burn fat much quicker. No lifting results in the body burning away muscle AND fat.
Drink more water.
Read the /fit/ sticky: https://liamrosen.com/fitness.html

>DON'T
Eat refined sugars, they're terrible for you regardless of calories.
Eat processed foods.
Drink your calories (alcohol, soda, starbucks).
Freak out over a weight loss stall. Plateaus can last up to three weeks.
"Reward" yourself. Cheat days cheat only yourself.

>Other resources:
Loose skin, gyno & stretch marks: https://weight-loss-side-effects.netlify.app/
Reddit wiki: https://www.reddit.com/r/loseit/wiki/faq

Honestly I always try to look over my meals and find ways to optimize, but it's VERY hard for me to do so because while some things could be swapped out and I get better numbers, it ultimately comes back to "well, am I willing to give up food item x and swap it with y?" despite it being a smarter choice, my sanity still needs to stay in place. I'm already below deficit as is with adequate protein, but if I could optimize that even more I'd get even better results. I hold myself back on several swaps simply for the sake of my sanity of keeping items around I still enjoy. Swapping something I like for something I do not like for the sake of faster results is just not the way for me, I need a balance of compromise which I achieve via better meal rationing and no snacking. I think that's equally important but varies wildly from person to person. My only rule is I try ensure everything I eat is at least rich in protein or at least high in fiber for the sake of digestion.

A low blood sugar level can affect everyone differently. You'll learn how it makes you feel, although your symptoms may change over time.

Early signs of a low blood sugar level include:

sweating
feeling tired
dizziness
feeling hungry
tingling lips
feeling shaky or trembling
a fast or pounding heartbeat (palpitations)
becoming easily irritated, tearful, anxious or moody
turning pale
If a low blood sugar level is not treated, you may get other symptoms, such as:

weakness
blurred vision
confusion or difficulty concentrating
unusual behaviour, slurred speech or clumsiness (like being drunk)
feeling sleepy
seizures or fits
collapsing or passing out

Brain fog, or a lack of mental clarity, can have many causes, including stress, lack of sleep, poor diet, and certain medical conditions.

To improve your focus and mental clarity, I recommend the following:

Get enough sleep: Aim for 7-8 hours of sleep per night, and try to maintain a consistent sleep schedule.
Eat a healthy diet: Make sure you're getting enough vitamins and minerals by eating a variety of fruits, vegetables, and lean proteins. Avoid processed foods, sugary drinks, and excessive caffeine.
Manage stress: Find ways to manage stress, such as exercise, meditation, or therapy.
Try some brain-training exercises: you can use apps or games that are designed to help improve focus and concentration.
Avoid alcohol, tobacco and drugs like weed as they can worsen brain fog.

Here are some supplements that might help:

Omega-3 fatty acids, which can be found in fish oil supplements
Ginkgo biloba
Bacopa monnieri
Phosphatidylserine

It's important to keep in mind that these supplements are not proven to be effective for everyone and should be used with caution. It's always best to consult with a healthcare professional before taking any supplements.

>>69640465
There are levels. Basically what's bad about it isn't the muscle destruction (although that is bad), it's the fact that your muscle tissue is pretty toxic through your body, so your kidneys have to filter out all of that. If you damage one body part a bit, your kidneys will likely recovered (like what happened to you).

If you get rhabdo in multiple areas of your body and it's very severe, your kidneys can shut down if you don't get dialysis. If your kidneys get shot it becomes an issue where you'll need dialysis weekly until you get a transplant.

There are so many options out there for yo uto pick and it's honestly all very personal. You need to do a little bit of research yourself but I suggest looking at a basic "Classic bodybuilding split" or a "Push pull leg". Both of these are very proven to provide great results.

Youtube has shitloads of great information as well.

https://www.setforset.com/blogs/news/3-day-workout-split
https://www.muscleandstrength.com/workouts/upper-lower-4-day-gym-bodybuilding-workout


I enjoy the "Classic Bodybuilding split"
(See link above)

2. CLASSIC BODYBUILDER 3 DAY SPLIT
Session 1: Chest, Triceps
Session 2: Back, Biceps
Session 3: Legs, Shoulders


You can easily tweak these as you see fit to include lifts you enjoy or change the order to focus on a body area that you are lagging. Throw in abs somewhere you have free time.

Include the proven to give result lifts in each session with high reps. These exclude any warmup sets.

Day 1 - Chest + Tri
Bench Press 3 x 10-15 (Dumbbells is proven to be superior to the barbell but both work just fine)
Incline Press 3 x 10-15
Pec Flies 3 x 10-15
Dips 3 x 10-15
Skull crushers 3 x 10-15
Tri Extensions 3 x 10-15

Day 2 - Back + Bi
Pullsups/Lat Pulldown 3 x 10-15
Barbell or Cabel Rows 4 x 10-15
Deadlifts 3 x 5
Curls 3 x 15
Hammer Curls 3 x 15
Incline Curls 3 x 15
Incline Hammer Curls 3 x 15

Day 3 - Legs + Shoulders
Lunges 3 x 10
Squats 3 x 10-15
Leg Extension 3 x 10-15
Calf Raises (Throw in some shrugs at the top if using the machine)
Overhead press 3x 10-15
Arnold Press 3 x 10-15
Cable Lat Raise 3 x 10-15
Face pulls or single arm rear delt cable flies 3 x 10-15

(If you are working at a cable machine with 2 cables you can superset ab exercises on the other cable while you do your shoulder cable exercises)

>>69636006
>Are you supposed to be able to do that without arching your back a whole lot?
You don't arch your back at all.
You have your feet straight in front of you and somewhat forward, and don't pull in a straight line but a slight curve. Try over-gripping the bar, wrists bent over more parallel to ground, this makes the leverages easier/more intuitive. The cue is not to pull up but kinda initiating a lat pulldown, hard to explain. Might not actually touch the bar with your chest as it depends on flexibility and grip width, but that is your end position. Practice pausing each rep up there to build strength, it will be the weakest point of the pull.

>>69639045
Your calories seem a little low but YMMV - just make sure that if you're not gaining weight/strength you up your calories. Not anon from other thread but here's the problem with recomp - its subtle and slow. It is possible to do but its also possible that you try to recomp for 6 months and because you're screwing something up you end up doing fuck all for those 6 months. If you focus on distinct bulk/cut phases the changes you see will be bigger, occur faster and its easier to diagnose if something is going wrong. This comes at the cost of partially working against yourself (if you CAN get more muscular and less fat at the same time that would be awesome! but it requires being a) less experienced and b) getting pretty much everything right, which is not something someone who is less experienced is going to be good at)

>>69639787
The first phase is quite aggressive - not sure the context of the video but it might be warranted depending on the goal. I would always state that quick loss results in quick gains back - if you want the weight to come off and stay off you largely have to lose it slowly in a sustainable process you could imagine yourself continuing basically forever (if you can't its likely you'll just rebound when you stop the process)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>69650806
Its advisable to keep your protein intake stable (at the usual level of 1g/lb of body weight) and spread out into 4-5 meals on both workout and rest days. That's the theoretical optimum but it doesn't make a huge difference if you only have 3 meals, just makes it easier to eat as much protein as you need.

DOMs are a side effect of muscle fibre disruption/damage not the repair process itself, but obviously you don't get repair without damage (unless you don't eat!) so we use it as a proxy. Your muscles will be repairing themselves both with and without DOMs being present, don't worry about timing protein intake around DOMs or even workouts, timing has a very minor impact quantity is more important.

Let try to help you get started. You're going to do a ln AB full body split. Either do ABxABxx (mon-sun) or AxBxAxx BxAxBxx (2 weeks).

Workout A:
Squats 5 sets of 3
Bench Press 3x5
Barbell Row 3x5
Barbell Curl 3x10
Cable Fly 3x10
Decline Crunch with Twist 3x10

Workout B:
Deadlift 5x3
Overhead Press 3x5
(Assisted) Pullups 3x5
Skull Crushers 3x10
Lateral Raise 3x10
Calf Raise 3x10

Increase weight every time you manage to finish the planned amount of reps each set. Increase by as small a step as possible each time, depending on the plates you have available. If you can't make the planned amount of reps, keep using the same weight the next workout until you hit the requielred amount of reps to progress. If you fail an exercise for two workouts in a row, deload that exercise by two steps next workout and start again from there.

Here are a few easy and quick 1000 calorie meal ideas that don't include meat:

Scrambled eggs with veggies: Scramble 3-4 eggs in a pan with diced bell peppers, onions, and mushrooms. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Serve with 1/2 cup of brown rice or quinoa.

Chickpea and spinach curry: In a saucepan, sauté diced onions, garlic, and ginger in olive oil. Add a can of chickpeas, diced tomatoes, and a handful of spinach. Add curry powder, cumin, and salt to taste. Simmer for 15 minutes. Serve over 1 cup of cooked brown rice.

Black bean and sweet potato burrito bowl: Cook 1 cup of brown rice. In a separate pan, sauté diced sweet potatoes until tender. Add 1 can of black beans and a diced bell pepper. Season with cumin, chili powder, and salt to taste. Serve the bean and sweet potato mixture over the cooked brown rice.

Lentil and vegetable soup: In a pot, sauté diced onions, carrots, and celery in olive oil. Add 1 cup of green lentils, 4 cups of vegetable broth, and 1 can of diced tomatoes. Bring to a boil, then reduce the heat and simmer for 30 minutes. Season with thyme, rosemary, and salt to taste.

Tofu and vegetable stir-fry: Cut firm tofu into cubes and sauté in a pan with a little bit of oil. Add diced bell peppers, onions, and broccoli. Season with onions sauce, ginger, and garlic powder. Serve over 1 cup of cooked brown rice or quinoa.

These are just a few ideas, you can always add and subtract ingredients and spices to your taste, and also you can adjust the portion sizes to fit your calorie needs.

The safety and health benefits of consuming fruits and vegetables outweighs the potential risks of consuming small amounts of plastic particles that may be present in the packaging.

It is true that fruits and vegetables that are packaged in plastic can potentially transfer small amounts of plastic particles to the food. However, the risk from consuming these particles is considered to be low. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), the levels of these particles found in food are not high enough to cause any immediate health problems.

On the other hand, it's important to consider the benefits of consuming fresh fruits and vegetables, which are an important source of essential vitamins, minerals, and other nutrients. Eating a variety of fruits and vegetables is also important for maintaining a healthy diet.

It's also important to note that, as you mentioned, buying fruits and vegetables from farmers markets, or buying them directly from farmers, might reduce the risk of exposure to the plastic particles, but it also increases the risk of exposure to pathogens or other harmful microorganisms if the produce is not properly handled or if the sellers or shoppers are not following the hygienic regulations.

It is a trade-off, but the best option would be to buy fruits and vegetables from reputable sources, washing them thoroughly before consuming, and also storing them properly.

posts.com:
Many shoulder injuries and asymmetries are caused by damage to the nerve feeding the serratus anterior muscle, which results in a weak serratus anterior, and poor shoulder mechanics.

The typical gym exercises will not do much for the serratus anterior, especially if it is already not working very well. This is because benching involves locking the scapular against the bench, and because upward rotation exercises such as OHP don't train the serratus that much, and compensation patterns that avoid the weak serratus anterior often occur.

To train the serratus anterior, you should be doing pushups (pushup plus is not necessary), and some other exercises of which I have not yet played around with. Some exercises which don't work are the typical stupid physio exercises like wall slides and cable or band punches and all kinds of stupid dumb shit that physiotherapists do.

Often a weak serratus on one side will make it seems like your other side's shoulder is higher. This is not mentioned on the internet. When your serratus is weak, it will often feel "tight" and also feel like it is actually your lat. Your chest and lat on that side will look significantly smaller, partly because the serratus that sits underneath it is so weak and small.

That is all. Goodnight.

You are correct that the lower traps, along with the upper traps, do upwardly rotate the scapula and that the upper traps are often stronger than the lower traps in lifters. This can lead to an imbalance between the two muscles and can contribute to shoulder problems. In addition to the pushups and incline bench exercises, exercises that specifically target the lower traps and other scapular muscles such as the infraspinatus and teres minor, can be helpful in addressing this imbalance. Some examples of exercises that can target these muscles include external rotation exercises with a cable or band, exercises that focus on scapular retraction such as pull-ups or rows and exercises that focus on scapular depression such as the prone Y, T, W and L raises.
It's also important to note that when training the external rotation, it's important to be aware of the body mechanics and movements to avoid overtraining one muscle and neglecting the other, and also to consult with a qualified professional to help you in creating a well-rounded training program.

So you're not really analysing this on the right level.

Let's step back a bit.

Life is the phenomenon of a self replicating machine using external energy to turn its environment into more of itself. That is something that explains every organism we know on this planet, from viruses, bacteria, mammals and us.

Now let's ignore all microbial life and focus purely on animals, because it's easier. We eat two things, (cellular) machinery and chemical energy. This maps to protein and vitamins and minerals (machinery) and sugars, carbs and fats (energy). Except animals can actually convert these between each other to a greater or lesser degree - remember this.

Now, life surrounds us animals. But the only source of external energy (for animals) is sunlight. Everything must come from the sun. Luckily plants surround us, and are concentrated sources of solar energy, they usually turn sunlight into sugars, and then into long starches and fibres. Humans can't digest most plant fibres (like cellulose). Either way, this means most animals eat plants. But other animals are concentrated sources of everything animals need to live. So some animals specialise in only eating other animals, they're literally bags of collected energy and machinery so there's this niche where a being could just eat other animals.

Now let's focus exclusively on humans. We do not have the ability to digest cellulose - gorillas have this, cows and sheep and goats have this - but we do not. So this means we have to eat fruits and vegetables and seeds only. We basically cannot eat leaves (though some exceptions apply). And we can function just fine doing this! Don't believe the propaganda, being vegan can be healthy. It's just really hard and most don't succeed.

This brings me to eating other animals. Its easy to get lots of essential nutrients from animals. We can digest them, after we've cooked them in fire.

Contd

I would strongly advise against using anabolic steroids, also known as "roids." They are illegal and can have serious side effects, both physical and mental.

Many of the gains made while on steroids will likely go away once you stop taking them, as the muscle growth is not natural and therefore not sustainable.

The percentage of people who experience negative side effects varies depending on the specific drug and dosage used, as well as the individual's physiology and physiology. However, common side effects of anabolic steroids include acne, hair loss, gynecomastia (breast development in men), and increased risk of heart disease and certain cancers. Additionally, long-term use can lead to addiction and mental health problems such as depression, aggression, and mood swings.

It's important to remember that building muscle through natural means takes time and dedication, but the results will be healthier and longer-lasting. Consult with a doctor or a trainer for a safe and legal way to reach your fitness goals.

Well you can 'intend' for your set to failure to look like that but it probably won't. Me personally, if I'm contracting hard & the weight takes me 4 seconds to lift, that is definitely my last rep. Also if you are using a combination of muscular contraction plus momentum to lift the weight, if you don't produce a certain threshold of force to achieve a certain level of momentum, you'll just fail, there won't be very much of a grind at all. If you're a performance athlete who uses speed to push through a sticking point, if you produce that force you'll finish the rep concentric in easily under 2 seconds, & if you don't you'll fail the rep without much grind to it.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>69644354
For ab exercises:
>hanging leg raises (toes to bar if you can)
>ab wheel rollouts
>weighted situps (weight behind head)
>l-sit progression
>dragon flags
If you care about obliques:
>side bends off of a 45 degree back extension (these fuck up your obliques big time, do very low volume and build your way up so you don't get DOMS for an entire week)
>suitcase carries
>pallof presses
>any rotational oblique exercise (most of them are harder to overload than the others here, russian twists would prob be the best option)
Start with 3-4 sets. I'd increase frequency instead of going above 4 sets (eg maybe do 4 sets 2 times per week, then later add 1 set to another day, eventually building up to 4 sets so you're doing 4 sets 3 times per week)
For reps, it depends on the exercise, but I'd say the 8-20 range is about where you want to be for abs.

>>69645163
I think the big lifts are fine if you alter them for your purposes. The way they are typically performed is fine for strength but for hypertrophy you can alter them to be a lot better for both growing muscle and reducing injury risk. ATG high-bar/front/ssb squats instead of parallel low-bar squats, deficit RDLs instead of deadlifts, minimal arch medium grip larsen press instead of big arch wide grip bench press, etc. Slow eccentrics and pauses will make them even better for hypertrophy while reducing injury risk further, and you can modify them even more (wide grip on the deficit RDLs for even more ROM, 30 degree incline on the larsen press to reduce the weight further while biasing the upper pecs more, etc)
